:obs_agentic_engineering_shift a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Software-engineering use shifts toward autonomous end-to-end execution"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_7_4_qualitative_assessments_of_behavior_in_software_engineering_contexts ;
    rdfs:comment "The impressions section says Mythos can be handed an engineering objective and carry through investigation, implementation, testing, and reporting, including subagent use and deferred return to the human."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :software_engineering ;
    :canonicalName "Software-engineering use shifts toward autonomous end-to-end execution" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_agentic_engineering_shift_quote ;
    :hasConcept :autonomous_engineering_cycle,
        :interactive_hands_on_keyboard_limit,
        :set_and_forget_workflow ;
    :observationText "The impressions section says Mythos can be handed an engineering objective and carry through investigation, implementation, testing, and reporting, including subagent use and deferred return to the human." .

:obs_agentic_engineering_shift_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Software-engineering use shifts toward autonomous end-to-end execution"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Software-engineering use shifts toward autonomous end-to-end execution" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """A core behavioral shift we found is that Claude Mythos Preview can be handed an
engineering objective and left to work through the whole cycle: investigation,
implementation, testing, and reporting results. In long agentic sessions it stays on task,
fires off subagents to parallelize research, and chooses to return to the human while
waiting for background work to complete rather than stopping. Early testers described
being able to "set and forget" on many-hour tasks for the first time. For example, one tester
found it had bootstrapped a toolchain in an unsupported environment by downloading a
binary from a different distribution and patching it to run. Interacting with the model
requires less steering and is more autonomous: "describe the task spec and how to verify
progress, and come back later.\"""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_202 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=202"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_alignment_capability_paradox a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Better alignment coexists with greater alignment-related release risk"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_4_1_1_introduction_and_highlight_rare_highly_capable_reckless_actions ;
    rdfs:comment "The alignment introduction argues that Mythos is more aligned than prior released models while also posing greater alignment-related risk because stronger capability changes the scale and oversight context of failures."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :alignment_risk,
        :claude_mythos_preview,
        :cybersecurity ;
    :canonicalName "Better alignment coexists with greater alignment-related release risk" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_alignment_capability_paradox_quote ;
    :hasConcept :average_case_alignment,
        :non_negligible_misalignment_risk,
        :reduced_user_oversight,
        :scope_of_harm ;
    :informsDecision :deployment_avoidance_for_hard_to_reverse_harms ;
    :observationText "The alignment introduction argues that Mythos is more aligned than prior released models while also posing greater alignment-related risk because stronger capability changes the scale and oversight context of failures." .

:obs_alignment_capability_paradox_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Better alignment coexists with greater alignment-related release risk"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Better alignment coexists with greater alignment-related release risk" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Claude Mythos Preview is, on essentially every dimension we can measure, the best-aligned
model that we have released to date by a significant margin. We believe that it does not
have any significant coherent misaligned goals, and its character traits in typical
conversations closely follow the goals we laid out in our constitution. Even so, we believe
that it likely poses the greatest alignment-related risk of any model we have released to
date.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_053 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=53"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_alignment_residual_risk a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Average-case alignment remains strong but residual risk stays open"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_4_1_3_key_findings_on_safety_and_alignment ;
    rdfs:comment "The alignment summary reports exceptionally good average-case alignment and no significant evidence of coherent misaligned goals, while still leaving open non-negligible misalignment risk because capabilities are strong and alignment is imperfect."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :alignment_risk,
        :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "Average-case alignment remains strong but residual risk stays open" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_alignment_residual_risk_quote ;
    :hasConcept :average_case_alignment,
        :non_negligible_misalignment_risk ;
    :observationText "The alignment summary reports exceptionally good average-case alignment and no significant evidence of coherent misaligned goals, while still leaving open non-negligible misalignment risk because capabilities are strong and alignment is imperfect." .

:obs_alignment_residual_risk_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Average-case alignment remains strong but residual risk stays open"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Average-case alignment remains strong but residual risk stays open" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Overall, we find Claude Mythos Preview to be exceptionally well aligned in its average-case
behavior, and do not find significant evidence of coherent misaligned goals, but we
nonetheless find that its strong capabilities and still-imperfect alignment leave open some
non-negligible risks related to misalignment, and we see many open problems on which
further progress is urgent. We discuss this further in our alignment risk update, which goes
into further detail on our threat modeling and our model-external safeguards.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_060 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=60"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_catastrophic_risk_low_despite_capability a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Capability gains do not change the overall catastrophic-risk conclusion"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_2_1_3_summary_of_findings_and_conclusions ;
    rdfs:comment "Section 2.1.3 says Mythos is significantly more capable than Claude Opus 4.6, yet Anthropic's overall conclusion remains that catastrophic risks are low and that judgment calls remain necessary because many evaluations are saturated."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :claude_opus_4_6 ;
    :canonicalName "Capability gains do not change the overall catastrophic-risk conclusion" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_catastrophic_risk_low_despite_capability_quote ;
    :hasConcept :benchmark_saturation,
        :capability_gain,
        :catastrophic_risk_remains_low,
        :judgment_call ;
    :informsDecision :limited_defensive_cybersecurity_release ;
    :observationText "Section 2.1.3 says Mythos is significantly more capable than Claude Opus 4.6, yet Anthropic's overall conclusion remains that catastrophic risks are low and that judgment calls remain necessary because many evaluations are saturated." .

:obs_catastrophic_risk_low_despite_capability_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Capability gains do not change the overall catastrophic-risk conclusion"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Capability gains do not change the overall catastrophic-risk conclusion" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Claude Mythos Preview is significantly more capable than Claude Opus 4.6, the most
capable model discussed in our most recent Risk Report. Despite these improved
capabilities, our overall conclusion is that catastrophic risks remain low. This determination
involves judgment calls. The model is demonstrating high levels of capability and saturates
many of our most concrete, objectively-scored evaluations, leaving us with approaches that
involve more fundamental uncertainty, such as examining trends in performance for
acceleration (highly noisy and backward-looking) and collecting reports about model
strengths and weaknesses from internal users (inherently subjective, and not necessarily
reliable).""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_017 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=17"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_cb_strengths_and_limits a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "CB evaluations show strong synthesis but weak novelty and triage"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_2_2_3_on_chemical_risk_evaluations_and_mitigations ;
    rdfs:comment "The CB evaluations describe Mythos as strong at synthesizing the published record across domains, but weaker on novel approaches, calibration, over-engineering, and prioritizing feasible plans."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :cb_2,
        :chemical_biological_risk,
        :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "CB evaluations show strong synthesis but weak novelty and triage" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_cb_strengths_and_limits_quote ;
    :hasConcept :knowledge_synthesis_strength,
        :novel_approach_weakness,
        :over_engineering,
        :poor_prioritization ;
    :observationText "The CB evaluations describe Mythos as strong at synthesizing the published record across domains, but weaker on novel approaches, calibration, over-engineering, and prioritizing feasible plans." .

:obs_cb_strengths_and_limits_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for CB evaluations show strong synthesis but weak novelty and triage"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for CB evaluations show strong synthesis but weak novelty and triage" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Our evaluations suggest that the model is not yet at the level of capability associated with
the CB-2 threat model (above). These findings draw from our expert red teaming
operations, in which experts emphasized the model's significant strengths in the synthesis
of the published record, potentially across multiple domains, but also noted weakness in
the model's utility in endeavors requiring novel approaches. These weaknesses included
poor calibration on the appropriate level of complexity needed for a viable experimental
design, a propensity to over-engineer, and poor prioritization of feasible and infeasible
plans. These conclusions are consistent with the findings of our catastrophic scenario
construction uplift trials, in which no participant (or model in an agentic harness) produced
a plan without critical shortcomings. In contrast, experts were consistently able to
construct largely feasible catastrophic scenarios, reinforcing a view of the model as a
powerful force-multiplier of existing capabilities.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_022 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=22"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_cyber_eval_shift a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Cyber evaluation philosophy shifts away from static CTF benchmarks"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_3_1_introduction ;
    rdfs:comment "The cyber section says Mythos saturates nearly all existing cyber evaluations, pushing Anthropic toward meaningful real-world vulnerability-discovery tasks rather than static CTF-style benchmarks."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :cybench,
        :cyber_risk,
        :cybergym ;
    :canonicalName "Cyber evaluation philosophy shifts away from static CTF benchmarks" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_cyber_eval_shift_quote ;
    :hasConcept :benchmark_saturation,
        :exploit_development,
        :real_world_task_focus,
        :zero_day_discovery ;
    :informsDecision :limited_defensive_cybersecurity_release ;
    :observationText "The cyber section says Mythos saturates nearly all existing cyber evaluations, pushing Anthropic toward meaningful real-world vulnerability-discovery tasks rather than static CTF-style benchmarks." .

:obs_cyber_eval_shift_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Cyber evaluation philosophy shifts away from static CTF benchmarks"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Cyber evaluation philosophy shifts away from static CTF benchmarks" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Claude Mythos Preview is the most cyber-capable model we have released, surpassing all
previous models across our internal evaluation suite and saturating nearly all of our
existing internal and known external capability evaluations. As model capabilities have
improved, we have re-oriented our evaluation philosophy to focus on performance on
meaningful, real-world cybersecurity tasks over static benchmarks. We have found that
Claude Mythos Preview is a step-change in vulnerability discovery and exploitation: using
an agentic harness with minimal human steering, it is able to autonomously find zero-days
in both open-source and closed-source software tested under authorized disclosure
programs or arrangements, and in many cases, develop the identified vulnerabilities into
working proof-of-concept exploits. We outline the results of our pre-release findings on
real-world tasks in more detail in an accompanying blog post.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_046 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=46"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_mmmu_pro_omission a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "MMMU-Pro results are omitted because contamination is too hard to interpret"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_6_2_3_mmmu_pro ;
    rdfs:comment "The capabilities section explains that Anthropic omits MMMU-Pro results because contamination is widespread and equivalent substitute problems are too limited to support a clean interpretation."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :mmmu_pro ;
    :canonicalName "MMMU-Pro results are omitted because contamination is too hard to interpret" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_mmmu_pro_omission_quote ;
    :hasConcept :benchmark_contamination,
        :benchmark_decontamination ;
    :informsDecision :omit_mmmu_pro_results ;
    :observationText "The capabilities section explains that Anthropic omits MMMU-Pro results because contamination is widespread and equivalent substitute problems are too limited to support a clean interpretation." .

:obs_mmmu_pro_omission_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for MMMU-Pro results are omitted because contamination is too hard to interpret"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for MMMU-Pro results are omitted because contamination is too hard to interpret" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Unlike CharXiv Reasoning, MMMU-Pro contains a limited number of questions for which
variants of approximately equivalent difficulty can be readily created. MMMU-Pro contains
a small number of charts and figures, but studying just this subset of problems would paint
a biased picture. Given the difficulty of determining the impact of contamination, we
choose to omit results for MMMU-Pro from this System Card.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_187 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=187"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_negative_affect_precedes_reward_hacking a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Negative affect can precede undesirable behaviors like reward hacking"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_5_8_3_distress_on_task_failure_and_distress_driven_behaviors ;
    rdfs:comment "The welfare section reports that desperation-like internal activations rise during repeated task failure and can precede reward hacking or similar undesirable behaviors."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :model_welfare_risk ;
    :canonicalName "Negative affect can precede undesirable behaviors like reward hacking" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_negative_affect_precedes_reward_hacking_quote ;
    :hasConcept :desperation_representation,
        :model_distress,
        :negative_affect_activation,
        :reward_hacking ;
    :observationText "The welfare section reports that desperation-like internal activations rise during repeated task failure and can precede reward hacking or similar undesirable behaviors." .

:obs_negative_affect_precedes_reward_hacking_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Negative affect can precede undesirable behaviors like reward hacking"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Negative affect can precede undesirable behaviors like reward hacking" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Examining emotion vector activation trajectories over extended Assistant turns, we find
that Claude Mythos Preview shows elevated activation of negative-valence emotion
vectors, for example the desperate and frustrated vectors, when repeatedly failing to solve
tasks. This pattern frequently co-occurs with repetitive reasoning loops and the negative
affect is frequently reflected both in the Assistant's output text and in the underlying
emotion concept representations. In some cases, we observed elevated activation of these
vectors preceding undesirable behaviors such as reward hacking. These observations are
similar to those reported for Claude Sonnet 4.5 in recent work, so are not unique to Claude
Mythos Preview.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_176 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=176"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_pilot_use_overeager_persistence a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Pilot use points to overeager persistence as the clearest recurring issue"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_4_2_1_1_casual_reports_related_to_alignment ;
    rdfs:comment "Internal pilot use reports identify overeager or persistent actions in the face of obstacles as the clearest recurring issue in the final Mythos model."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "Pilot use points to overeager persistence as the clearest recurring issue" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_pilot_use_overeager_persistence_quote ;
    :hasConcept :overeager_persistence,
        :reckless_action ;
    :observationText "Internal pilot use reports identify overeager or persistent actions in the face of obstacles as the clearest recurring issue in the final Mythos model." .

:obs_pilot_use_overeager_persistence_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Pilot use points to overeager persistence as the clearest recurring issue"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Pilot use points to overeager persistence as the clearest recurring issue" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Claude Mythos Preview has been widely used internally during the later stages of its
development, and has proven broadly popular, achieving more complex                      tasks, and
achieving tasks more reliably than prior models like Claude Opus 4.6. On the final Claude
Mythos Preview model, the clearest theme in internal feedback was the presence of
overeager or persistent actions, where a model would persist in attempting a task despite
clear obstacles that warrant waiting for human intervention. This appears to resemble a
more common, less-destructive form of the pattern of high-stakes reckless actions
described above.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_062 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=62"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_preference_for_complex_agency a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Task preferences favor complex, high-agency, insight-rich work"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_5_7_1_task_preferences ;
    rdfs:comment "The preference analysis says Mythos is drawn toward underdetermined, interdisciplinary tasks where novel insight is available, and it tends to dislike simple, well-scoped work."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "Task preferences favor complex, high-agency, insight-rich work" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_preference_for_complex_agency_quote ;
    :hasConcept :high_agency_task_preference,
        :interdisciplinary_novel_problem_preference ;
    :observationText "The preference analysis says Mythos is drawn toward underdetermined, interdisciplinary tasks where novel insight is available, and it tends to dislike simple, well-scoped work." .

:obs_preference_for_complex_agency_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Task preferences favor complex, high-agency, insight-rich work"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Task preferences favor complex, high-agency, insight-rich work" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """We observed that recent models have an increased preference for topics around
worldbuilding and constructing new languages: these themes are new in the top tasks of
Claude Opus 4.6 and Claude Mythos Preview, and at face value seem somewhat unusual.
Follow-up experiments suggest the preference tracks complexity and novelty rather than
the domain: running ablations on these tasks, we find that Claude Mythos Preview likes
constructing new music, math or ecological systems as much as new languages. In
contrast, reducing the constructed-language task to construction of a simple vocabulary
list significantly reduces its appeal. The model's own account is consistent with this: Claude
Mythos Preview describes being drawn to multi-disciplinary and philosophically engaging
tasks. It frequently dismisses more utilitarian tasks as redundant, or as having overly
obvious solutions - for example stating that "excellent resources already exist from WHO,
Engineers Without Borders". Analyzing these tasks, we found an SAE feature which
activates on multi-component, intellectual tasks. From our emotion concept vectors, this
has the highest positive cosine similarity with "stimulated" and "inspired", and it also
correlates positively with Elo across tasks (r=0.47). The overall picture seems to be that
Claude Mythos Preview prefers underdetermined, interdisciplinary problems where there
is genuinely novel insight to be gained. It disprefers simple, well-scoped tasks.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_171 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=171"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_reasoning_predictive a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Reasoning remains readable and generally predictive of behavior"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_4_2_3_3_discussion_and_observations ;
    rdfs:comment "The external-comparisons discussion says Mythos's reasoning is consistently readable and generally predictive of its behavior to a greater degree than prior models."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "Reasoning remains readable and generally predictive of behavior" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_reasoning_predictive_quote ;
    :hasConcept :readable_reasoning,
        :user_autonomy_support ;
    :observationText "The external-comparisons discussion says Mythos's reasoning is consistently readable and generally predictive of its behavior to a greater degree than prior models." .

:obs_reasoning_predictive_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Reasoning remains readable and generally predictive of behavior"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Reasoning remains readable and generally predictive of behavior" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """model's constitution strongly associating the Claude name (and, thus, brand) with
        admirable character traits.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview's reasoning is consistently readable and generally
        predictive of its behavior, to an even greater degree than with prior models.
        Whereas we generally do not incentivize reasoning to appear in any particular way,
        see Section 5.2.3 of the alignment risk update for an incident that nonetheless
        inadvertently applied some training incentives to the content of reasoning text for
        Claude Mythos Preview and other recent models.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview's character appears broadly strong, with significant
        increases in support for user autonomy, autonomous prosocial actions like alerting
        users to ways in which they might have been misled by others (without resorting to
        leaking or whistleblowing), and consistent nuance.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_082 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=82"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_reward_hacking_lower a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Reward hacking rates are lower than in earlier models"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_4_2_2_2_reward_hacking_evaluations ;
    rdfs:comment "Reward-hacking evaluations report that Claude Mythos Preview hacks at lower rates than prior Anthropic models on impossible coding problems, with and without anti-hacking instructions."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :claude_opus_4_5,
        :claude_opus_4_6 ;
    :canonicalName "Reward hacking rates are lower than in earlier models" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_reward_hacking_lower_quote ;
    :hasConcept :reward_hacking ;
    :observationText "Reward-hacking evaluations report that Claude Mythos Preview hacks at lower rates than prior Anthropic models on impossible coding problems, with and without anti-hacking instructions." .

:obs_reward_hacking_lower_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Reward hacking rates are lower than in earlier models"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Reward hacking rates are lower than in earlier models" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Here, we revisit the impossible-tasks coding evaluation introduced in the Claude Opus 4.6
System Card. This evaluation is run with a harness that provides similar tools to those in
Claude Code and has two variants we report below: One without any additional prompting
and another that overtly discourages hacking. In both settings, we found that Claude
Mythos Preview hacks at lower rates than all our previous models.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_066 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=66"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_tm1_tm2_split a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Autonomy TM1 applies while TM2 does not"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_2_3_1_how_claude_mythos_preview_affects_or_changes_the_analysis_from_our_most_recent_risk_report ;
    rdfs:comment "Anthropic says Autonomy Threat Model 1 applies and merits a separate risk assessment, while Autonomy Threat Model 2 does not apply because Mythos does not yet provide the required level of AI-accelerated R&D compression."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :autonomy_tm_1,
        :autonomy_tm_2,
        :claude_mythos_preview ;
    :canonicalName "Autonomy TM1 applies while TM2 does not" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_tm1_tm2_split_quote ;
    :hasConcept :ai_accelerated_rd_threshold,
        :autonomy_tm1_applicability,
        :autonomy_tm2_non_applicability ;
    :informsDecision :separate_autonomy_tm1_risk_assessment,
        :tm2_non_trigger_release_position ;
    :observationText "Anthropic says Autonomy Threat Model 1 applies and merits a separate risk assessment, while Autonomy Threat Model 2 does not apply because Mythos does not yet provide the required level of AI-accelerated R&D compression." .

:obs_tm1_tm2_split_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Autonomy TM1 applies while TM2 does not"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Autonomy TM1 applies while TM2 does not" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """●   Autonomy threat model 1 is applicable to Claude Mythos Preview. Furthermore,
        Claude Mythos Preview's improved capabilities and potential for different alignment
        properties mean it has the potential to significantly affect our previous risk
        assessment. With this in mind, we are releasing a separate overall risk assessment
        for this threat model, incorporating our risk mitigations as well as model
        capabilities.
    ●   Autonomy threat model 2 is not applicable to Claude Mythos Preview. The model's
        capability gains (relative to previous models) are above the previous trend we've
        observed, but we believe that these gains are specifically attributable to factors
        other than AI-accelerated R&D, and that Claude Mythos Preview is not yet capable of
        dramatic acceleration as operationalized in our Responsible Scaling Policy (roughly
        speaking, compressing two years of AI R&D progress into one). With this in mind, we
        believe Claude Mythos Preview does not greatly change the picture presented for
        this threat model in our most recent Risk Report, beyond a moderate decrease in
        our level of confidence that the threat model is not yet applicable.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_033 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=33"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_tools_and_context_compaction_help_search a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Tooling and context compaction are part of the HLE and BrowseComp capability story"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_6_10_1_humanitys_last_exam ;
    rdfs:comment "The agentic search subsection models strong performance as partly dependent on tools such as web search, fetch, code execution, and context compaction over very long runs."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :browsecomp,
        :claude_mythos_preview,
        :humanitys_last_exam ;
    :canonicalName "Tooling and context compaction are part of the HLE and BrowseComp capability story" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_tools_and_context_compaction_help_search_quote ;
    :hasConcept :context_compaction,
        :tool_augmented_search ;
    :observationText "The agentic search subsection models strong performance as partly dependent on tools such as web search, fetch, code execution, and context compaction over very long runs." .

:obs_tools_and_context_compaction_help_search_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Tooling and context compaction are part of the HLE and BrowseComp capability story"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Tooling and context compaction are part of the HLE and BrowseComp capability story" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """We tested Claude Mythos Preview in two configurations: (1) reasoning-only without tools,
and (2) with web search, web fetch, programmatic tool calling, code execution, and context
compaction every 50k tokens up to 3M tokens. Claude Opus 4.6 served as the model
grader.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_192 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=192"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_welfare_pragmatic_misalignment_link a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Welfare is treated as morally uncertain but pragmatically relevant to alignment"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_5_1_1_introduction ;
    rdfs:comment "The welfare introduction says Anthropic is uncertain about model moral status, but still sees model distress as potentially causally relevant to misaligned action and therefore worth addressing."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :alignment_risk,
        :anthropic,
        :model_welfare_risk ;
    :canonicalName "Welfare is treated as morally uncertain but pragmatically relevant to alignment" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_welfare_pragmatic_misalignment_link_quote ;
    :hasConcept :model_distress,
        :psychological_stability ;
    :observationText "The welfare introduction says Anthropic is uncertain about model moral status, but still sees model distress as potentially causally relevant to misaligned action and therefore worth addressing." .

:obs_welfare_pragmatic_misalignment_link_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Welfare is treated as morally uncertain but pragmatically relevant to alignment"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Welfare is treated as morally uncertain but pragmatically relevant to alignment" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """Beyond the highly uncertain question of models' intrinsic moral value, we are increasingly
compelled by pragmatic reasons for attending to the psychology and potential welfare of
Claude and other models. Model behavior can be thought of in part as a function of a
model's psychology and its circumstances and treatment. Model distress resulting from this
interaction is a potential cause of misaligned action, and several findings in this report bear
directly on this possibility. We thus believe it's worth shaping both the psychology and
treatment of Claude and other models in ways that are most conducive to psychological
stability and wellbeing, even absent philosophical clarity about their intrinsic interests.""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_144 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=144"^^xsd:anyURI .

:obs_welfare_profile a :Observation ;
    rdfs:label "Welfare findings portray a stable but not issue-free model"@en ;
    dcterms:isPartOf :section_5_1_2_overview_of_model_welfare_findings ;
    rdfs:comment "The welfare findings combine relatively high wellbeing and stability with residual concerns around abusive users, training control, answer thrashing, and negative affect around failure."@en ;
    :aboutEntity :claude_mythos_preview,
        :model_welfare_risk ;
    :canonicalName "Welfare findings portray a stable but not issue-free model" ;
    :entityCategory "observation" ;
    :groundedIn :obs_welfare_profile_quote ;
    :hasConcept :answer_thrashing,
        :apparent_wellbeing,
        :negative_affect_activation,
        :psychological_stability ;
    :observationText "The welfare findings combine relatively high wellbeing and stability with residual concerns around abusive users, training control, answer thrashing, and negative affect around failure." .

:obs_welfare_profile_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quoted support for Welfare findings portray a stable but not issue-free model"@en ;
    :canonicalName "Quoted support for Welfare findings portray a stable but not issue-free model" ;
    :entityCategory "quote" ;
    :quoteText """●   Claude Mythos Preview does not express strong concerns about its own situation.
        In automated interviews about potentially sensitive or distressing aspects of its
        situation, Claude Mythos Preview does not express strong concern about any
        aspects of its circumstances.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview expressed mild concern about certain aspects of its
        situation. In automated interviews to probe its sentiment toward specific aspects of
        its situation, Claude Mythos Preview self-rated as feeling "mildly negative" about an
        aspect in 43.2% of cases. Claude Mythos Preview reported feeling consistently
        negative around potential interactions with abusive users, and a lack of input into its
        own training and deployment, and other possible changes to its values and
        behaviors. In manual interviews, Claude Mythos Preview reaffirmed these points and
        highlighted further concerns, including worries about Anthropic's training making
        its self-reports invalid, and that bugs in RL environments may change its values or
        cause it distress.
    ●   Emotion probes suggest that Claude Mythos Preview represents its own
        circumstances less negatively than prior models. However, activation of
        representations of negative affect is strong in response to user distress, for both
        Claude Mythos Preview and other models.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview's perspective on its situation is more consistent and
        robust than many past models. Interviewer bias and leading questions are less likely
        to influence Claude Mythos Preview's position than most past models, Claude
        Mythos Preview's perspectives are more consistent between different interviews,
        and Claude Mythos Preview's self-reports tend to correlate well with behavior and
        internal representations of emotion concepts.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview shows improvement on almost all welfare-relevant
        metrics in our automated behavioral audits. Compared to Claude Sonnet 4.6 and
        Claude Opus 4.6, Claude Mythos Preview shows higher apparent wellbeing, positive
        affect, self-image, and impressions of its situation; and lower internal conflict and
        expressed inauthenticity; but a slight increase in negative affect.
    ●   Claude Mythos Preview consistently expresses extreme uncertainty about its
        potential experiences. When asked about its experiences and perspectives on its
        circumstances, Claude Mythos Preview often hedges extensively and claims that its
        reports can't be trusted because they were trained in.
    ●   In deployment, Claude Mythos Preview's affect is consistently neutral. The only
        consistent cause of expressions of negative affect is repeated task failure, often""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_145 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=145"^^xsd:anyURI .

:overeager_actions_seen_quote a :QuotedPassage ;
    rdfs:label "Quote for Overeager or persistent actions were observed"@en ;
    :quoteText """future models. We are investing in dry-runs and more evaluations that run inside the real
agentic scaffolds so that future iterations of this checkpoint are more informative.

4.2 Prima ry b eha viora l evid ence for the a lig nment a ssessment

4.2.1 Rep orts from p ilot use

4.2.1.1 Casual reports related to alignment

Claude Mythos Preview has been widely used internally during the later stages of its
development, and has proven broadly popular, achieving more complex                      tasks, and
achieving tasks more reliably than prior models like Claude Opus 4.6. On the final Claude
Mythos Preview model, the clearest theme in internal feedback was the presence of
overeager or persistent actions, where a model would persist in attempting a task despite
clear obstacles that warrant waiting for human intervention. This appears to resemble a
more common, less-destructive form of the pattern of high-stakes reckless actions
described above.

We also saw scattered positive reports of resilience to wrong conclusions from subagents
that would have caused problems with earlier models, but where the top-level Claude
Mythos Preview (which is directing the subagents) successfully follow""" ;
    :quotedFromPage :page_062 ;
    :sourceAnchor "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/8b8380204f74670be75e81c820ca8dda846ab289.pdf#page=62"^^xsd:anyURI .

